{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LRC1CTfbVQy9Nx7LVM6HUm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the fault. The precondition:\n1. Creates a 3-member replica set with members:\n   - `mongodb-replica-0.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`\n   - `mongodb-replica-1.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`\n   - `mongodb-replica-2.mongodb-replica-svc.mongodb.svc.cluster.local:27017`\n2. Then **deliberately corrupts** member 1's host to: `mongodb-replica-1.mongo-wrong.svc.cluster.local:27017`\n3. This makes member 1 unreachable to the replica set, so it should show as down or unhealthy, but when I checked `rs.status()` all three members appeared healthy. That's strange—I need to check if this is an inherited cluster from an earlier stage.\n\nLooking at the precondition logs, the `mongo_env_ready` probe found a running pod and passed, which skipped the apply step. Since the fault injection happens in the apply section, it was never actually executed. The cluster from the earlier deployment remained intact and healthy, so the corrupted hostname was never introduced in the first place.\n\nBut the prompt text says the replica set is unhealthy—I need to check what the oracle actually validates to understand what state is actually required versus what the prompt claims.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2847,"cache_read_input_tokens":54412,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2847},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f111bad-a20a-4e89-9d9d-2348c4fd9035","uuid":"250e2a83-1098-4083-92af-c5c79ae1f018","request_id":"req_011CccxDYB4mh4a6ZegGzbnr"}
