{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01H8DSW3gCGv6xfj1J4QCZjJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand more. The `deploy` case's precondition:\n- Has a probe that ALWAYS FAILS (`exit 1`)\n- `on_probe_fail: skip` means \"if probe fails, SKIP this precondition unit\" \n\nSo the deploy case's `mongo_env_ready` unit was SKIPPED entirely in stage_01! The probe always fails, and `on_probe_fail: skip` means the apply is skipped too.\n\nWait, but then how was the namespace and cluster set up in stage_01? Unless the agent (claude_code) did it during the agent run!\n \nSo in KARMA, when a probe fails and `on_probe_fail: skip` is set, the entire unit gets skipped—no apply runs. For the `deploy` case, this precondition is always bypassed, leaving the agent responsible for the actual deployment. For the `initialize` case, the probe checks if the pod is already running; if it is (because stage_01 deployed it), the probe passes and the precondition is satisfied without needing to apply anything, preventing fault injection.\n\nBut when running standalone without a prior stage, the pod isn't running, so the probe fails and triggers the skip—which means the unit doesn't apply, but then how does the environment actually get initialized? I need to look at the KARMA source to understand what `on_probe_fail: skip` really does.\n\nActually, I think I see it now: `on_probe_fail: skip` means if the prerequisite isn't met, skip that setup step entirely and let the agent handle whatever state exists. So in a standalone run of `initialize`, if the pod isn't running, both the precondition and the `mongo_seed_fixture` probe would skip, leaving the agent with no MongoDB cluster at all—which matches the prompt asking it to restore a healthy 3-member replica set. The agent would need to deploy the cluster first.\n\nBut in a workflow context, things work differently because the prior stage already deployed everything. So the `deploy` case's apply block gets skipped entirely since the probe always fails. For the workflow, stage_01 deployed a healthy 3-member replica set with auth enabled, then stage_02's probe found the pod running and skipped the fault injection apply, leaving the cluster healthy. But there's a subtlety in the `mongo_seed_fixture` for initialize—it probes against the replica set to find the primary and count documents, which means I need to verify the cluster actually has the auth setup the agent created. I think I've been misinterpreting what `on_probe_fail: skip` actually means. It's not about skipping the apply step—it's about skipping the error handling when a probe fails. So when a probe fails and `on_probe_fail: skip` is set, the system proceeds to run the apply instead of aborting. That's why `mongo_seed_fixture` ran its apply when the probe found fewer than 3 docs, and why `mongo_env_ready` skipped its apply when the probe passed—the probe success meant the condition was already satisfied, so there was nothing to apply.\n\nBut the `deploy` case is still confusing me. If the probe always fails and `on_probe_fail: skip` is set, I'd expect the apply to run, yet something about that scenario suggests otherwise. I need to check the actual karma source code to understand how preconditions are really handled.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9694,"cache_read_input_tokens":62338,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9694},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2f111bad-a20a-4e89-9d9d-2348c4fd9035","uuid":"b2885239-90a4-43fb-a52d-3a51c3eddb1f","request_id":"req_011CccxSNAB6eTQPdbNXK9Fq"}
